{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AqtARnhC6ZErEsiJEMbswY","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 14-2: Tech Debt Gate in Story Selection\n     2→\n     3→## Status: verifying\n     4→\n     5→<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n     6→\n     7→<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->\n     8→\n     9→## Story\n    10→\n    11→As a developer,\n    12→I want TD stories prioritized before new feature work,\n    13→So that debt gets paid before it accumulates further.\n    14→\n    15→## Acceptance Criteria\n    16→\n    17→1. Given `epic-TD` has 3 backlog stories and a feature epic has 5 backlog stories, when `selectNextStory()` runs, then a TD backlog story is selected first <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    18→2. Given all TD stories are `done`, when `selectNextStory()` runs, then feature epic stories are selected normally <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    19→3. Given `epic-TD` has backlog stories AND a non-TD story is `in-progress`, when `selectNextStory()` runs, then the in-progress story is still selected (TD gate only applies to Tier D backlog selection) <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    20→4. Given `epic-TD` has backlog stories AND a non-TD story is `verifying`, when `selectNextStory()` runs, then the verifying story is selected (TD gate does not override higher tiers) <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    21→5. Given `epic-TD` has no stories (no `TD-` prefixed keys in state), when `selectNextStory()` runs, then normal backlog selection applies (lexicographic + attempt-count ordering) <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    22→6. Given a TD story is `in-progress`, when `selectNextStory()` runs, then it follows normal Tier A priority (in-progress always wins, regardless of TD or feature) <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    23→7. Given `npm run build` runs after all changes, then TypeScript compilation succeeds with zero errors <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    24→8. Given `npm test` runs after all changes, then all existing tests pass with zero regressions <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    25→9. Given no new file created for this story, when line count is checked, then no modified file exceeds 300 lines <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    26→\n    27→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    28→\n    29→- [x] Task 1 (AC: 1, 5): Add TD gate logic to `selectNextStory()` in `selector.ts`\n    30→  - [x]After sorting candidates by tier, check if the winner is Tier 3 (backlog)\n    31→  - [x]If winner is Tier 3 AND is not a `TD-` prefixed story, scan candidates for any `TD-` prefixed Tier 3 stories\n    32→  - [x]If pending TD backlog stories exist, re-sort to place `TD-` stories before non-TD stories within Tier 3\n    33→  - [x]If no TD backlog candidates exist, proceed with normal selection\n    34→\n    35→- [x] Task 2 (AC: 1): Add test — TD backlog stories selected before feature backlog stories\n    36→  - [x]State with `TD-1-fix-catch-blocks` (backlog) and `15-1-ci-file-size-gate` (backlog)\n    37→  - [x]Expect `TD-1-fix-catch-blocks` selected\n    38→\n    39→- [x] Task 3 (AC: 2): Add test — all TD stories done, normal selection resumes\n    40→  - [x]State with `TD-1-fix-catch-blocks` (done), `TD-2-add-logging` (done), and `15-1-ci-file-size-gate` (backlog)\n    41→  - [x]Expect `15-1-ci-file-size-gate` selected\n    42→\n    43→- [x] Task 4 (AC: 3): Add test — in-progress non-TD story wins over TD backlog\n    44→  - [x]State with `TD-1-fix-catch-blocks` (backlog) and `15-1-ci-file-size-gate` (in-progress)\n    45→  - [x]Expect `15-1-ci-file-size-gate` selected (Tier A beats Tier D)\n    46→\n    47→- [x] Task 5 (AC: 4): Add test — verifying non-TD story wins over TD backlog\n    48→  - [x]State with `TD-1-fix-catch-blocks` (backlog) and `15-1-ci-file-size-gate` (verifying)\n    49→  - [x]Expect `15-1-ci-file-size-gate` selected (Tier B/C beats Tier D)\n    50→\n    51→- [x] Task 6 (AC: 5): Add test — no TD stories, normal backlog selection\n    52→  - [x]State with `15-1-ci-file-size-gate` (backlog) and `15-2-eslint-rules` (backlog)\n    53→  - [x]Expect normal lexicographic + attempt-count ordering\n    54→\n    55→- [x] Task 7 (AC: 6): Add test — TD story in-progress follows normal Tier A priority\n    56→  - [x]State with `TD-1-fix-catch-blocks` (in-progress) and `15-1-ci-file-size-gate` (backlog)\n    57→  - [x]Expect `TD-1-fix-catch-blocks` selected (Tier A, not because of TD gate)\n    58→\n    59→- [x] Task 8 (AC: 1): Add test — TD backlog story with fewer attempts selected over TD story with more attempts\n    60→  - [x]State with `TD-1-fix-catch` (backlog, attempts: 3) and `TD-2-add-logging` (backlog, attempts: 1)\n    61→  - [x]Expect `TD-2-add-logging` selected (fewer attempts tiebreak preserved within TD)\n    62→\n    63→- [x] Task 9 (AC: 7): Run `npm run build` — TypeScript compilation succeeds\n    64→- [x] Task 10 (AC: 8): Run `npm test` — all existing tests pass, zero regressions\n    65→- [x] Task 11 (AC: 9): Verify all modified files are under 300 lines\n    66→\n    67→## Dev Notes\n    68→\n    69→### Architecture Compliance\n    70→\n    71→- **Decision 6c (Tech Debt Gate):** This story implements the third mechanism from architecture-v3.md Decision 6: tech debt gate in story selection. Before selecting ANY Tier D (backlog) story from a feature epic, check if `epic-TD` has pending work. If yes, process TD stories first. This ensures accumulated debt gets addressed before new features start.\n    72→- **Decision 7 (300-line limit, NFR5):** All modified files must stay under 300 lines.\n    73→\n    74→### Implementation Guidance\n    75→\n    76→#### Where to modify\n    77→\n    78→The tech debt gate goes in `src/modules/sprint/selector.ts` in the `selectNextStory()` function. The current function:\n    79→\n    80→1. Iterates all stories, filters out terminal and retry-exhausted\n    81→2. Assigns priority tiers (0=in-progress, 1=verifying-with-proof, 2=verifying, 3=backlog/ready/review)\n    82→3. Sorts by tier, then attempts, then key\n    83→4. Returns the first candidate\n    84→\n    85→The gate should be inserted **after sorting** but **before returning**. If the winner is Tier 3, check if any `TD-` prefixed Tier 3 candidates exist. If so, prefer them.\n    86→\n    87→#### Implementation approach\n    88→\n    89→Modify the sort comparator to add a secondary sort dimension within Tier 3:\n    90→\n    91→```typescript\n    92→candidates.sort((a, b) => {\n    93→  // Primary: priority tier ascending\n    94→  if (a.tier !== b.tier) return a.tier - b.tier;\n    95→  // TD gate: within Tier 3 (backlog), TD- stories come first\n    96→  if (a.tier === 3) {\n    97→    const aIsTd = a.key.startsWith('TD-');\n    98→    const bIsTd = b.key.startsWith('TD-');\n    99→    if (aIsTd !== bIsTd) return aIsTd ? -1 : 1;\n   100→  }\n   101→  // Secondary: fewer attempts first\n   102→  if (a.story.attempts !== b.story.attempts) {\n   103→    return a.story.attempts - b.story.attempts;\n   104→  }\n   105→  // Tertiary: lexicographic key order\n   106→  return a.key.localeCompare(b.key);\n   107→});\n   108→```\n   109→\n   110→This approach is simpler than a post-sort gate check. It preserves existing behavior for Tiers 0-2 and only modifies the ordering within Tier 3. Within the TD group, the existing tiebreakers (attempts, then key) still apply.\n   111→\n   112→#### Why sort-based over gate-based\n   113→\n   114→The existing technical note in the old story file suggests a post-selection gate (`if tdEpic ... return pendingTd[0]`). The sort-based approach is better because:\n   115→1. It preserves attempt-count tiebreaking within TD stories\n   116→2. It doesn't require checking `state.epics` — the `TD-` prefix in the story key is sufficient\n   117→3. It's a 3-line change inside the existing sort comparator\n   118→4. It doesn't introduce a second code path\n   119→\n   120→#### Key constraint\n   121→\n   122→The gate ONLY applies within Tier 3 (backlog/ready/review). In-progress and verifying stories always take priority regardless of whether they are TD or feature stories. This is by design — Decision 6c says \"before selecting ANY Tier D story.\"\n   123→\n   124→### Testing Guidance\n   125→\n   126→- **Vitest** (not Jest). Use `vi.fn()`, `vi.mock()`, `vi.mocked()`.\n   127→- Imports: `import { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest'`\n   128→- Use existing test helpers: `buildSprintState()`, `buildStoryEntry()` from `helpers.js`\n   129→- Follow the existing `makeState()` helper pattern already in `selector.test.ts`\n   130→- All new tests go in the existing `src/modules/sprint/__tests__/selector.test.ts` file\n   131→- The file currently has 274 lines — adding ~80 lines of tests keeps it well under 300 if structured compactly, but may push close. If needed, use `it.each` patterns to compress.\n   132→\n   133→### Previous Story Intelligence (14-1)\n   134→\n   135→- Story 14-1 completed successfully. It created `epic-TD`, `TD-N-slug` stories, and the retro-to-sprint pipeline.\n   136→- The `selector.ts` file is currently 123 lines — well within budget for a 3-line addition.\n   137→- `selector.test.ts` is 274 lines — adding tests will push it. Monitor the 300-line limit carefully.\n   138→\n   139→### Key Observations About Existing Code\n   140→\n   141→1. **`selectNextStory()`** (selector.ts:65-123) — the sort at line 100-109 is where the TD gate goes.\n   142→2. **`selector.test.ts`** (274 lines) — close to the 300-line limit. Use `it.each` for compact test cases if needed.\n   143→3. **No dependency on `state.epics`** — the `TD-` key prefix is sufficient to identify tech debt stories. No need to check if `epic-TD` exists in the epics map.\n   144→4. **`buildSprintState()`** already supports `epics` override, but it's not needed for this story since the gate uses key prefix detection.\n   145→\n   146→### References\n   147→\n   148→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-architecture-v3.md lines 333-357] — Story 14-2 epic definition + Decision 6c\n   149→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-v3.md lines 336-357] — Decision 6 (Retro-to-Sprint Pipeline), section 6c\n   150→- [Source: src/modules/sprint/selector.ts] — Story selection logic to modify\n   151→- [Source: src/modules/sprint/__tests__/selector.test.ts] — Existing selector tests to extend\n   152→\n   153→## Files to Change\n   154→\n   155→- `src/modules/sprint/selector.ts` — Add TD gate within Tier 3 sort comparator (3-line change in the sort function)\n   156→- `src/modules/sprint/__tests__/selector.test.ts` — Add 7 new test cases for TD priority, empty TD, mixed TD and feature stories, higher-tier override\n   157→\n   158→## Senior Developer Review (AI)\n   159→\n   160→**Date:** 2026-03-25\n   161→**Reviewer:** Adversarial code review\n   162→**Outcome:** Approved with fixes applied\n   163→\n   164→### Findings\n   165→\n   166→| # | Severity | Description | Resolution |\n   167→|---|----------|-------------|------------|\n   168→| 1 | MEDIUM | AGENTS.md missing TD gate documentation for selector.ts | Fixed: added Decision 6c reference |\n   169→| 2 | MEDIUM | Shorthand status variables (`bl`, `dn`, `ip`, `vf`) polluting describe scope, reducing readability | Fixed: replaced with typed `it.each` and inline status strings |\n   170→| 3 | MEDIUM | No test for case-sensitivity edge case (`td-` lowercase) | Fixed: added test confirming uppercase-only match |\n   171→| 4 | LOW | No architecture decision reference in selector.ts comment | Not fixed (low priority) |\n   172→| 5 | LOW | `keyToTitle` produces \"Td 1 fix\" for \"TD-1-fix\" (acronym mangling) | Not fixed (pre-existing, not in scope) |\n   173→\n   174→### Additional tests added during review\n   175→- TD gate applies to `ready` status (not just `backlog`)\n   176→- Lowercase `td-` prefix is NOT treated as tech debt (case-s